  "stem": "<p class=\"stem_paragraph \">In the right triangle shown above, what is the length of&nbsp;<span class=\"math_expression \"><span class=\"math-container\"><img align=\"middle\" role=\"math\" class=\"math-img\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" alt=\"line P Q\"></span></span>&nbsp;?</p>\n",
  "answerOptions": [],
  "keys": [],
  "rationale": "<p class=\"tcp-fd3ea050-58f4-4b16-a81d-baba01ecbcd1\">The correct answer is 4. Triangle <span class=\"italic\">PQR </span>has given angle measures of 30<!--StartFragment-->&deg;<!--EndFragment--> and 90<!--StartFragment-->&deg;<!--EndFragment-->, so the third angle must be 60&deg; because the measures of the angles of a triangle sum to 180<!--StartFragment-->&deg;<!--EndFragment-->. For any special right triangle with angles measuring 30&deg;, 60&deg;, and 90&deg;, the length of the hypotenuse (the side opposite the right angle) is 2<span class=\"italic\">x</span>, where <span class=\"italic\">x</span> is the length of the side opposite the 30<!--StartFragment-->&deg;<!--EndFragment--> angle. Segment <span class=\"italic\">PQ</span> is opposite the 30<!--StartFragment-->&deg;<!--EndFragment--> angle. Therefore, 2(<span class=\"italic\">PQ</span>)<span class=\"italic\"></span> = 8 and <span class=\"italic\">PQ </span>= 4.</p>\n",
